RHFContentBlockingKeysGetterField.tsx_VP.defaultMessage:
Document deduplication helps you avoid creating duplicate records. For example, preventing a second contact from being created with the same email address.

When enabled, every time you create a new document, Superego checks that another similar document doesn't already exist, and warns you if it does.

This is done by associating to each document a set of "blocking keys": small, deterministic fingerprints derived from the documentâ€™s content (for example, a normalized email address, or a last-name + postal-code pair) that almost uniquely identify a document. If two documents share a blocking key, theyâ€™re likely duplicates.

RHFContentBlockingKeysGetterField.tsx_fN.defaultMessage:
The content blocking keys of a document are a list of stringsâ€”derived from the document's contentâ€”that uniquely identify the document based on its data. Documents sharing a blocking key are considered duplicates.

The blocking keys getter is the TypeScript function that derives these keys from the document content.

The keys should be deterministic (same content produces same keys) and sensitive to meaningful changes while ignoring non-meaningful differences like whitespace.

RHFContentSummaryGetterField.tsx_BmNFs6.defaultMessage:
The content summary of a document is aRecord'' â€”derived from the document's contentâ€”that contains its most important bits of information. The properties of the record are displayed when showing a "summary view" of the document; for example, in tables, where each property becomes a column.

Content summary getter is the TypeScript function that derives the summary from the document content.

The property names of the summary object can be prefixed by attributes that configure the behavior of the UIs that render the summary. For example, when rendering a table of documents, '{position:0,sortable:true,default-sort:asc}' First Name makes First Name the first column, makes it sortable, and sets the column as the default sort order of the table.

Remote.tsx_s8FZNF.defaultMessage:
You can sync a collection with an external data source (a remote). When a remote is configured, it becomes the source of truth for that collection.

The collection isn't necessarily an exact replica of the remote. Documents pulled from the remote are transformed to match your collection's schema via your fromRemoteDocument mapping, and you can filter which remote documents are synced.

To set up a remote, configure a connector to the external data source.

Some connectors support only syncing down from the remote, making the collection read-only. Others also support syncing up to the remote, so creates, updates, and deletes in the collection are propagated to the remote.

More info at https://superego.dev/connectors.

SchemaTab.tsx_/WLKzQ.defaultMessage:
Every time you want to change the schema of a collection (e.g., to add, change, or remove properties), you need to create a new collection version. The process involves the following steps:

  1. Implement the schema changes you want to make.
  2. Update the collection's content summary getter to reflect those changes.
  3. Write a migration function to convert documents from the previous schema to the updated schema.
